rl":"https://lobste.rs/s/pfqxak/claude_desktop_installs_undocumented"},{"short_id":"dfe90i","created_at":"2026-04-19T19:43:12.000-05:00","title":"Theseus, a static Windows emulator","url":"https://neugierig.org/software/blog/2026/04/theseus.html","score":25,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"carlana","user_is_author":false,"tags":["retrocomputing","windows"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/dfe90i","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/dfe90i/theseus_static_windows_emulator"},{"short_id":"7ovybf","created_at":"2026-04-19T19:35:58.000-05:00","title":"This Week in Plasma: Per-Screen Virtual Desktops and Wayland Session Restore","url":"https://blogs.kde.org/2026/04/18/this-week-in-plasma-per-screen-virtual-desktops-and-wayland-session-restore/","score":24,"flags":0,"comment_count":2,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"yokljo","user_is_author":false,"tags":["linux"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/7ovybf","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/7ovybf/this_week_plasma_per_screen_virtual"},{"short_id":"0wq9ns","created_at":"2026-04-19T18:47:02.000-05:00","title":"High-performance 2D graphics rendering on the CPU using sparse strips","url":"https://ethz.ch/content/dam/ethz/special-interest/infk/inst-pls/plf-dam/documents/StudentProjects/MasterTheses/2025-Laurenz-Thesis.pdf","score":15,"flags":0,"comment_count":1,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"technetium","user_is_author":false,"tags":["graphics","pdf","performance","rust"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/0wq9ns","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/0wq9ns/high_performance_2d_graphics_rendering"},{"short_id":"u1a0fd","created_at":"2026-04-19T18:17:56.000-05:00","title":"The fastest way to match characters on ARM processors?","url":"https://lemire.me/blog/2026/04/19/the-fastest-way-to-match-characters-on-arm-processors/","score":4,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"fanf","user_is_author":false,"tags":["assembly","performance"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/u1a0fd","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/u1a0fd/fastest_way_match_characters_on_arm"},{"short_id":"ghsneu","created_at":"2026-04-19T16:12:33.000-05:00","title":"Defense in Depth: A Practical Guide to Python Supply Chain Security","url":"https://bernat.tech/posts/securing-python-supply-chain/","score":2,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"\u003cp\u003eLayer your defenses and don’t trust any single control. Use Ruff with security rules to catch bugs in your code before they ship. Pin all your dependencies with cryptographic hashes using uv lock or uv pip compile --generate-hashes so nobody can swap out packages on you. Run pip-audit in CI to catch known CVEs before they hit production. Generate SBOMs with CycloneDX so when the next Ultralytics-style compromise drops, you can answer “are we affected?” in minutes instead of days.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIf you’re publishing packages, ditch the long-lived API tokens and switch to Trusted Publishing with OIDC. This generates attestations automatically via Sigstore, linking your packages back to source repos. Organizations running internal mirrors can add a 7-day delay to let the community be your canary - but only if you’ve got the infrastructure to maintain it.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eNothing here is perfect. Hash pinning stops tampering but won’t save you from a malicious package you installed on day one. Scanning finds known CVEs but misses zero-days. Attestations prove where code came from, not whether it’s safe. That’s why you layer them - when one control fails, the others catch it. Start with linting and pinning for quick wins, add scanning and SBOMs next, then level up to advanced stuff as you mature.\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"Layer your defenses and don’t trust any single control. Use Ruff with security rules to catch bugs in your code before they ship. Pin all your dependencies with cryptographic hashes using uv lock or uv pip compile --generate-hashes so nobody can swap out packages on you. Run pip-audit in CI to catch known CVEs before they hit production. Generate SBOMs with CycloneDX so when the next Ultralytics-style compromise drops, you can answer “are we affected?” in minutes instead of days.\r\n\r\nIf you’re publishing packages, ditch the long-lived API tokens and switch to Trusted Publishing with OIDC. This generates attestations automatically via Sigstore, linking your packages back to source repos. Organizations running internal mirrors can add a 7-day delay to let the community be your canary - but only if you’ve got the infrastructure to maintain it.\r\n\r\nNothing here is perfect. Hash pinning stops tampering but won’t save you from a malicious package you installed on day one. Scanning finds known CVEs but misses zero-days. Attestations prove where code came from, not whether it’s safe. That’s why you layer them - when one control fails, the others catch it. Start with linting and pinning for quick wins, add scanning and SBOMs next, then level up to advanced stuff as you mature.","submitter_user":"gaborjbernat","user_is_author":true,"tags":["python","security"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/ghsneu","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/ghsneu/defense_depth_practical_guide_python"},{"short_id":"it5xwh","created_at":"2026-04-19T16:12:29.000-05:00","title":"Stupid RCU Tricks: Corner-Case RCU Implementations","url":"https://people.kernel.org/paulmck/stupid-rcu-tricks-corner-case-rcu-implementations","score":5,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"fanf","user_is_author":false,"tags":["osdev"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/it5xwh","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/it5xwh/stupid_rcu_tricks_corner_case_rcu"}]